First, simplify the numerator and denominator: - The numerator is \(\log(n^2) - (\log n)^2 = 2 \log n - (\log n)^2 = -\log n (\log n - 2)\). - The denominator is \(\log n - 3\). Thus, the expression inside the square root becomes: \[ \frac{-\log n (\log n - 2)}{\log n - 3} \] We need this fraction to be non-negative. Let \( x = \log n \). The inequality becomes: \[ \frac{-x(x - 2)}{x - 3} \geq 0 \] Analyzing the critical points \( x = 0 \), \( x = 2 \), and \( x = 3 \), we find the solution for \( x \) is \( [0, 2] \cup (2, 3) \). Converting back to \( n \): - \( x = 0 \) corresponds to \( n = 1 \). - \( x \in (2, 3) \) corresponds to \( 10^2 < n < 10^3 \), i.e., \( 100 < n < 1000 \). Thus, the valid integers \( n \) are: - \( n = 1 \) - \( n \) from 100 to 999 inclusive Counting these integers: - \( n = 1 \) is 1 integer. - \( n \) from 100 to 999 inclusive is \( 999 - 100 + 1 = 900 \) integers. Summing these, we get \( 1 + 900 = 901 \). \[ \boxed{901} \]
